JavaScript ArrayBuffer:


- 💡An ArrayBuffer is fixed a block of memory, often used to store typed arrays.
- On top of this block, you can create different views that interpret the bits as numbers, bytes, or other data
    types


#) Creating an ArrayBuffer:
    - 💡Use new ArrayBuffer() to create a new ArrayBuffer.
    - eg: Create a 16-byte ArrayBuffer:

        // Create an ArrayBuffer
        const myBuf = new ArrayBuffer(16);

        // Get the length in bytes
        let len = myBuf.byteLength;

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Number of bytes are " + len;   // 16
    
    - 💡The size of an ArrayBuffer is specified in bytes.
    - 💡The byteLength property represents the size.
    - ⚠️Once created, the size can not be changed.


#) Accessing an ArrayBuffer:
    - 💡The ArrayBuffer does not have methods to read and write data.
    - 💡You must always use a view to access the data.
    - 💡Typed Arrays and DataViews provide a way to read and write numeric values to an ArrayBuffer.
        Common typed arrays are:
            -> Uint8Array - 8-bit unsigned integers
            -> Int16Array - 16-bit signed integers
            -> Int32Array - 32-bit signed integers
            -> Float32Array - 32-bit floating point numbers
            -> Float64Array - 64-bit floating point numbers
    

#) Using an Uint8Array:
    - ⚠️Each Uint8 uses 1 byte. (values for writing range from 0 to 255)

        <script>
            // create 8-byte ArrayBuffer
            const myBuf = new ArrayBuffer(8)

            // create a Uint8Array view
            const view = new Uint8Array(myBuf);

            // 💡write max 8 values (since Uint8 uses 1 byte, we can write 8 Uint8 values in 8 byte memory)
            view[0] = 10;
            view[2] = 128;
            view[1] = 255;
            view[3] = 300;  // ⚠️300 is more than 1 byte

            // read values
            let r0 = view[0];
            let r1 = view[1];
            let r2 = view[2];
            let r3 = view[3];

            // display values
            document.getElementById('demo').innerHTML = `The values are ${r0}, ${r1}, ${r2}, ${r3}`;
        </script>

        o/p:    The values are 10, 255, 128, 44

        💡⚠️ 300 is not a valid write value since it is more that 1 byte. But JS does not throw an error.
            It silently forces the value into 1 byte(8 bits).
            So why 44?

                300 = 100101100 (9 bits)

            But a Uint8Array only keeps 8 bits → it drops the leftmost bit:

                00101100   (8 bits)  = 44


#) Using an Int32Array:
    - 💡Each Int32 uses 4 bytes. 
        <script>
            // Create an 12-byte ArrayBuffer
            const myBuf2 = new ArrayBuffer(12);

            // Create an Int32Array view
            const view2 = new Int32Array(myBuf2);

            // 12 bytes = Max 3 Int32 values (since Int32 uses 4 byte, we can write 3 Int32 values in a 12 byte memory)
            view2[0] = 100000;
            view2[1] = 200000;
            view2[2] = -300000;


            // Read values
            let v0 = view2[0];
            let v1 = view2[1];
            let v2 = view2[2];

            // Display values
            document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = `Values are ${v0}, ${v1}, ${v2}`;
        </script>


#) Using a DataView:
    - A DataView is a more flexible view for an ArrayBuffer.
    - 💡A DataView lets you read and write values of different types (Int8, Uint16, Float32, etc.).
    - 💡A DataView also lets you read and write values at any byte offset.

        <script>
            // Create an ArrayBuffer
            const myBuf = new ArrayBuffer(8);

            // Create a DataView
            const view = new DataView(myBuf);

            // Write a 32-bit integer at byte offset 0
            view.setInt32(0, 123456);

            // Write a 16-bit integer at byte offset 4
            view.setInt16(4, 32000);

            // Read the values
            let v1 = view.getInt32(0);
            let v2 = view.getInt16(4);

            // Display values
            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Values are " + v1 + ", " + v2;  
        </script>

        o/p:    Values are 123456, 32000


#) Slicing an ArrayBuffer:
    - 💡You can make a copy of a part of an ArrayBuffer using the slice() method. It returns a new ArrayBuffer
        calwith bytes from the specified range.

            <script>    
                const myBuf = new ArrayBuffer(8);

                // create a Uint8Array view
                const view = new Uint8Array(myBuf);

                // fill with value 0 to 7
                for (let i = 0; i < view.length; i++) {
                    view[i] = i;
                }

                // create a copy of bytes from 2 to 5 (not including 5)
                const sliced = myBuf.slice(2, 5);
                const sliceView = new Uint8Array(sliced);

                document.getElementById('demo').innerHTML = view + "<br> sliced: " + sliceView;
            </script>

            o/p:    0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7
                    sliced: 2,3,4
    
    - The slice() method creates a new buffer.
    - 💡The slice() method does not share memory with the original buffer.


#) Converting Strings:
    - 1️⃣ Converting a string to an ArrayBuffer (UTF-8):

        <script>
            function stringToArrayBuffer(string) {
                // Create an object that knows how to convert strings into bytes using UTF-8
                let encoder = new TextEncoder();
                return encoder.encode(string).buffer;
            }

            const myBuf = stringToArrayBuffer("Hello");

            const myView = new Uint8Array(myBuf);
            let len1 = myBuf.byteLength;

            document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML = 
            "ArrayBuffer: " + myView + " <br> length(in bytes):  " + len1;
        </script>

        o/p:    ArrayBuffer: 72,101,108,108,111
                length(in bytes): 5
        
        -> 💡Converted ArrayBuffer is the ASCII (decimal) representation of letters in a string
    

    - 2️⃣ Converting an ArrayBuffer to a String (UTF-8):

        <script>
            function arrayBufferToString(buffer) {
                // Create an object that knows how to convert bytes into string using UTF-8
                const decoder = new TextDecoder();
                return decoder.decode(new Uint8Array(buffer));
            }

            const encoder = new TextEncoder();
            const myBuff = encoder.encode("Hello ArrayBuffer").buffer;

            let text = arrayBufferToString(myBuff);

            document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = "String is: " + text;
        </script>

        o/p:    String is: Hello ArrayBuffer


#) Sharing ArrayBuffer (SharedArrayBuffer):
    - 💡An ArrayBuffer is not shared between threads by default.
    - 💡To share memory between workers, JavaScript provides SharedArrayBuffer.
    - 💡It behaves like ArrayBuffer, but its contents can be shared and used with Atomics.

        <script>
            if (Window.crossOriginIsolated) {
                buffer = new SharedArrayBuffer(16);
            } else {
                buffer = new ArrayBuffer(16);
            }

            const sharedView = new Int32Array(buffer);

            sharedView[0] = 42;

            let numb = sharedView[0];

            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Shared is " + numb;
        </script>
    
    - ⚠️Browsers may require special security headers to enable SharedArrayBuffer (COOP/COEP).



#) Summary:
    👉 ArrayBuffer is a low-level object representing a fixed-size block of memory
    👉 You cannot read or write directly to an ArrayBuffer
    👉 You use views (typed arrays or DataView) to access an ArrayBuffer
    👉 Typed arrays are good for uniform numeric data
    👉 DataView is good for mixed or structured data
    👉 Use slice() to copy parts of an ArrayBuffer
    👉 Use a SharedArrayBuffer and Atomics for shared-memory concurrency


#) Common Use Cases:
    👉 Working with binary data from files (e.g., images, videos, audio).
    👉 Handling binary network protocols (WebSockets, WebRTC, etc.).
    👉 Performing performance-critical numeric computations.
    👉 Interoperability with WebAssembly or other low-level APIs.


